<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-388-084  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 388 084.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  June 27 1989 v3 n25 p24(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Upgrading the image of programmers. (editorial)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT/><TEXT>Upgrading the image of programmersandM;In an age in which the frontiers of outer space are traversed by humansdefying the earth's gravity, it is fitting that the pioneering astronauts areacclaimed for their courage and ingenuity.andM;The same cannot be said for the elite corps of programmers who areinstrumental in developing the software and hardware that hold the spacecraftand its fragile  contents aloft.andP;  The hacker heroes who toil to launch thespace shuttle and to bring about the revolution in desktop computers are moreknown by the general public  for their supposed nocturnal lifestyle andscruffy appearance than for their programming deeds.andM;Most recently, programmers and the term &quot;hacker&quot; have been associated withthe increase in computer viruses, pirated source code and other computercrimes.andM;The 150 programmers who attended the MacHack conference in Ann Arbor, Mich.,andO;earlier this month are more indicative of the community of hackers whocontinue to push the envelope in search of new ways to dazzle their peers andinvent new programming paradigms.andP;  For three days and nights, these virtuososlabored to come up with a hack on the Macintosh just for the fun of it.andO;Eventually, some of those hacks could turn into products that define new usesfor the Macintosh.andM;Programmers don't need to be treated like rock stars, but they at leastshould be recognized as explorers who can make important contributions tosociety.andO;</TEXT></DOC>